  "text": "A common control signal for oscillatory-based BCI is the sensorimotor rhythm (SMR), wherein mu (8-12Hz) and beta (18-26Hz) bands desynchronize over the sensorimotor cortex contralateral to an actual or imagined movement. The SMR is very similar to that of the oscillatory component of the MRCP. While SMR-based BCIs can facilitate nuanced, endogenous BCI control (enabling high dimensional control of cursors or even prosthetic limbs) they are not without their practical challenges. As signals, SMRs tend to be weak and highly variable across and within subjects, conventionally demanding user-training (neurofeedback) and long calibration times (20 minutes) in order to achieve reasonable performance [CITATION_1] .",
